The trace starts after the verifier is already deployed, so the constructor is a real opportunity here. I’m shifting the implementation to pre-open the tiny poisoned stake during deployment using a deterministic V2 flashswap, then use `executeOnOpportunity()` only for realization. That keeps the exploit path intact and directly addresses the current “no seed JUICE” failure.
codex
I have enough context to rewrite the verifier. The edit is focused on two changes: acquire a persistent seed amount honestly from public JUICE V2 pool dust during deployment, then pre-open the poisoned stake so `executeOnOpportunity()` can be purely the harvest/drain leg.
